# AI Server-Only and Schema-Validated

## Intent

Constrain AI work to the approved server-side architecture and safety model. No client app may call Ollama directly. All AI must flow through a shared server-side service boundary with standardized validation, timeouts, and fallback behavior.

## Allowed Architecture

- **Runtime**: Ollama with a Qwen small instruct model; exact version chosen by environment config
- **Access**: AI functionality exposed through a shared server-side service boundary
- **Service boundary responsibilities**:
  - Prompt building
  - Model selection
  - Output validation (Zod schemas)
  - Logging and tracing
  - Error handling
  - Safety fallback behavior

## Initial AI Use Cases

- Workout text cleanup
- Exercise extraction from rough trainer input
- Chat summarization
- Suggested staff replies
- Campaign copy drafting

## Safety Rules

- **Server-side only**: AI requests are server-side only; no client may call Ollama
- **Prompt templates**: Versioned in code
- **Output validation**: All outputs must be validated against Zod schemas
- **Timeouts**: Required for every AI call
- **Retry policies**: Required
- **Feature flag**: Must exist to disable AI safely
- **Sensitive prompts**: Do not store long-term without strong justification
- **Locale**: AI input and output handling must support explicit locale control for user-facing text

## Required Implementation Checklist

When adding or changing AI functionality:

- [ ] AI call goes through the shared server-side service boundary
- [ ] Prompt templates are versioned in code
- [ ] Output schema (Zod) is defined and enforced
- [ ] Timeout is configured
- [ ] Retry policy is configured
- [ ] Feature flag exists to disable the flow
- [ ] Locale is passed for user-facing input/output
- [ ] Logging and tracing are present
- [ ] Error handling and safety fallback behavior are implemented

## Prohibited Patterns

- Client apps calling Ollama directly
- AI outputs used without Zod schema validation
- AI calls without timeouts
- AI calls without retry policies
- Shipping AI features without a kill-switch feature flag
- Storing sensitive raw prompts long-term without documented justification
- AI user-facing text without explicit locale control
- Introducing a second AI service boundary alongside the approved one
